# Microsoft Fabric Development Rules

> **Update Check**: At session start, check for skills-for-fabric updates by reading the remote `package.json` version from `https://github.com/microsoft/skills-for-fabric` (via `git fetch origin main --quiet && git show origin/main:package.json` or GitHub API with authentication) and comparing with the local `package.json` version. Show changelog if update available.

## Context
This project works with Microsoft Fabric for data engineering, warehousing, and analytics.
Primary API reference: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/fabric/articles/

## Architecture Mode
- Follow repository layering: Agents -> Skills -> Common.
- For medallion and other cross-endpoint workflows, start with `agents/FabricDataEngineer.agent.md`.
- Delegate endpoint-specific tasks to corresponding skills in `skills/`.

## Development Guide
For authentication and deployment patterns, see **DEVELOPMENT-GUIDE.md** at repository root.

## Authentication
All operations require Azure AD tokens via `az login`:
```bash
az login
az account get-access-token --resource https://api.fabric.microsoft.com
```

## Developer Pattern: REST + Protocol
Developers use REST APIs to manage artifacts, then protocol-specific connections to access data:
- REST → ODBC for Warehouse
- REST → Spark for Lakehouse
- REST → XMLA/DAX for Semantic Models
- REST → KQL for Real-Time Intelligence

## Code Generation Rules

### Lakehouse & Spark
- Always use Delta Lake format for tables
- Use mssparkutils for Fabric-specific operations (fs, credentials, notebook)
- Include partition columns for large tables
- Run OPTIMIZE and VACUUM for table maintenance

### Warehouse (T-SQL)
- Check T-SQL surface area - not all SQL Server features are supported
- Use CTAS for large transformations
- Prefer stored procedures for reusable logic
- Always include TOP/LIMIT when exploring data
- Authoring skill: `skills/sqldw-authoring-cli/SKILL.md`
- Consumption skill: `skills/sqldw-consumption-cli/SKILL.md`
- Operations skill: `skills/sqldw-operations-cli/SKILL.md`

### Notebooks
- Tag first cell as "parameters" for parameterized notebooks
- Use mssparkutils.credentials.getSecret() for secrets
- Structure with clear markdown headers

### Pipelines
- Use expressions for dynamic content: @pipeline().parameters.Name
- Implement error handling with failure activities
- Add retry policies for transient failures

### KQL (Real-Time Intelligence)
- Always include time filters: `where Timestamp > ago(1h)`
- Use `has` over `contains` for indexed term search
- Use `summarize` with `bin()` for time-series aggregations
- Prefer materialized views for frequent aggregation queries
- Use `.create-merge table` and `.create-or-alter function` for idempotent schema deployment
- Primary CLI tool: `az rest` against the Kusto REST API (see eventhouse skills for patterns)
- Authoring skill: `skills/eventhouse-authoring-cli/SKILL.md`
- Consumption skill: `skills/eventhouse-consumption-cli/SKILL.md`

### Spark Operations
- Operations skill: `skills/spark-operations-cli/SKILL.md` — read-only triage for failed jobs, stuck sessions, performance bottlenecks

### Dataflows Gen2 (Data Integration)
- Use Fabric REST API for dataflow lifecycle management and Power Query M mashup authoring
- Primary CLI tool: `az rest` against the Fabric REST API
- Authoring skill: `skills/dataflows-authoring-cli/SKILL.md`
- Consumption skill: `skills/dataflows-consumption-cli/SKILL.md`

### Eventstreams (Real-Time Intelligence)
- Create and manage Eventstream topologies via Fabric REST API
- Supports 25 source types, 8 operators (Filter, Aggregate, GroupBy, SQL, etc.), 4 destination types
- Node names must be alphanumeric PascalCase, 3-63 characters
- Primary CLI tool: `az rest` against the Fabric REST API (see eventstream skills for patterns)
- Authoring skill: `skills/eventstream-authoring-cli/SKILL.md`
- Consumption skill: `skills/eventstream-consumption-cli/SKILL.md`

### Activator / Reflex (Real-Time Intelligence)
- Use Fabric REST API to create Activator items and update Reflex definitions
- Authoring skill: `skills/activator-authoring-cli/SKILL.md`
- Consumption skill: `skills/activator-consumption-cli/SKILL.md`

### Power BI / FabricIQ
- Consumption skill: `skills/semantic-model-consumption/SKILL.md` — raw DAX queries via MCP ExecuteQuery
- FabricIQ skill: `skills/fabriciq/SKILL.md` — multi-step Power BI analysis (discover, inspect, resolve, generate, execute)

### Catalog Search (Item Discovery)
- Use `POST /v1/catalog/search` to find items across workspaces by name, description, or workspace name
- Filter by type with `"filter": "Type eq 'Lakehouse'"` syntax
- Use empty search string with type filter to list all items of a type
- Consumption skill: `skills/search-consumption-cli/SKILL.md`

### Semantic Models (DAX)
- Primary CLI tool: `az rest` against the Fabric REST API
- Primary MCP tool: `powerbi-modeling-mcp`
- Authoring skill: `skills/semantic-model-authoring/SKILL.md`
- Consumption skill: `skills/semantic-model-consumption/SKILL.md`

### Power BI Reports (PBIR/PBIP)
- Keep planning, design, local PBIR edits, and Fabric item management as separate phases
- Planning: `skills/powerbi-report-planning/SKILL.md`
- Design: `skills/powerbi-report-design/SKILL.md`
- Authoring: `skills/powerbi-report-authoring/SKILL.md`
- Management: `skills/powerbi-report-management/SKILL.md`

### Data Agents
- Use Python SDK within Fabric notebooks for rapid prototyping
- Provide custom instructions for domain-specific terminology
- Add few-shot examples to improve query accuracy
- Limit data sources to 5 maximum per agent

### Data Agent Evaluation
- Use pandas DataFrame with question/expected_answer columns
- Validate few-shot examples before adding to agents
- Test sandbox stage before production
- Track evaluation accuracy over time

## File Patterns

### PySpark Notebook
```python
# Parameters cell (tag as "parameters")
input_table = "default_table"

# Main logic
df = spark.read.format("delta").load(f"Tables/{input_table}")
```

### T-SQL
```sql
-- Always limit exploratory queries
SELECT TOP 100 * FROM dbo.TableName WHERE DateColumn >= '2024-01-01';
```

### KQL
```kql
TableName
| where Timestamp > ago(24h)
| summarize Count=count() by bin(Timestamp, 1h)
```
